#Methodology

-Applied different JOIN types to the same dataset to observe output differences
-Used FULL JOIN to combine all records from both tables
-Used RIGHT JOIN to prioritize shipment data
-Used LEFT JOIN to prioritize customer data
-Applied filtering using WHERE and sorting using ORDER BY

#Followed a structured approach:

Select JOIN type → Apply filters → Interpret results → Translate to business value

#Key Insights

-JOIN type selection directly impacts which records are included or excluded
-FULL JOIN provides a complete dataset view across both tables
-RIGHT JOIN ensures all shipment data is retained, even without matching customers
-LEFT JOIN ensures all customer data is retained, even without shipments
-Filtering and sorting refine datasets for operational and analytical use

#Recommendations

-Use FULL JOIN for comprehensive data audits and validation
-Use RIGHT JOIN when shipment-level analysis is the priority
-Use LEFT JOIN when customer-level insights are required
-Apply filtering and sorting to focus on high-value or operationally relevant data

